{"title_page": "Simon Harmer", "text_new": "{{short description|South African cricketer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use South African English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Simon Harmer\n| image = Simon Harmer.jpg\n| caption = Harmer in 2019\n| country = South Africa\n| fullname = Simon Ross Harmer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1989|2|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Pretoria]], [[Transvaal Province]], South Africa\n| heightft = \n| heightinch = \n| heightm = \n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[off break]]\n| role = [[All-rounder]]\n| international = true\n| testdebutdate = 2 January\n| testdebutyear = 2015\n| testdebutagainst = West Indies\n| testcap = 321\n| lasttestdate = 25 November\n| lasttestyear = 2015\n| lasttestagainst = India\n| club1 = [[Eastern Province cricket team|Eastern Province]]\n| year1 = {{nowrap|2009\u20132011}}\n| club2 = [[Warriors (cricket team)|Warriors]]\n| year2 = {{nowrap|2011\u2013present}}\n| clubnumber2 = 11\n| club3 = [[Border cricket team|Border]]\n| year3 = 2016\n| club4 = [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]]\n| year4 = {{nowrap|2017\u2013present}}\n| clubnumber4 = 11\n| club5 = [[Jozi Stars]]\n| year5 = 2018\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 5\n| runs1 = 58\n| bat avg1 = 11.60\n| 100s/50s1 = 0/0\n| top score1 = 13\n| deliveries1 = 1,148\n| wickets1 = 20\n| bowl avg1 = 29.40\n| fivefor1 = 0\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 4/61\n| catches/stumpings1 = 1/\u2013\n| column2 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches2 = 145\n| runs2 = 4,292\n| bat avg2 = 24.52\n| 100s/50s2 = 2/22\n| top score2 = 102[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries2 = 34,602\n| wickets2 = 608\n| bowl avg2 = 27.80\n| fivefor2 = 34\n| tenfor2 = 6\n| best bowling2 = 9/95\n| catches/stumpings2 = 140/\u2013\n| column3 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| matches3 = 83\n| runs3 = 1,002\n| bat avg3 = 20.44\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/0\n| top score3 = 44[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries3 = 3,858\n| wickets3 = 78\n| bowl avg3 = 42.29\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 4/42\n| catches/stumpings3 = 55/\u2013\n| column4 = [[Twenty20|T20]]\n| matches4 = 92\n| runs4 = 635\n| bat avg4 = 19.24\n| 100s/50s4 = 0/0\n| top score4 = 43\n| deliveries4 = 1,659\n| wickets4 = 68\n| bowl avg4 = 30.72\n| fivefor4 = 0\n| tenfor4 = 0\n| best bowling4 = 4/19\n| catches/stumpings4 = 44/\u2013\n| date = 29 September\n| year = 2019\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/southafrica/content/player/432960.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n'''Simon Ross Harmer''' (born 10 February 1989) is a South African professional [[cricket]]er. He plays as an [[all-rounder]], a right handed middle order batsman and an off-break bowler, for [[Warriors cricket team|Warriors]] and has played five [[Test cricket|Test]] matches for [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]].\n\nHarmer debuted for Warriors in the 2010\u20132011 first class season against the Cape Cobras claiming 5/98 in the first innings and 1/53 in the second innings to go along with his 46 and 69 runs with the bat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/southafrica/content/player/432960.html#bataves|title=Simon Harmer|website=Cricinfo|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> He became a regular fixture in Warriors side in the 2011\u20132012 side, ending the season as leading wicket taker in his full rookie season, claiming 44 wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6838;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records \u2013 Records \u2013 SuperSport Series, 2011/12 \u2013 Most wickets \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThese performances earned him a call up for the 3rd Test against West Indies in 2014/15,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-west-indies-2014-15/content/story/815081.html|title=Harmer's call-up a warning to Tahir|publisher=|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> where he made his Test match debut for South Africa [[West Indian cricket team in South Africa in 2014\u201315|against the West Indies]] on 2 January 2015 at [[Newlands Cricket Ground|Newlands]], [[Cape Town]].<ref name=\"Test\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/722333.html |title=West Indies tour of South Africa, 3rd Test: South Africa v West Indies at Cape Town, Jan 2\u20136, 2015 |accessdate=2 January 2015 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> He took his debut Test wicket by bowling [[Devon Smith]] in the last over before the lunch break on day one<ref name=\"Test\" /> and ended the innings with figures of 3/71 from 26 overs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-west-indies-2014-15/engine/match/722333.html|title=3rd Test: South Africa v West Indies at Cape Town, Jan 2\u20136, 2015 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the 2017 season, Harmer signed for [[Essex County Cricket Club]] as a [[Kolpak ruling|Kolpak]] player.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/37719936 |title=Simon Harmer: South Africa all-rounder joins Essex on Kolpak deal |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 October 2016 |accessdate=21 October 2016 }}</ref> In June, in the [[2017 County Championship]], Harmer took 9 wickets for 95 runs in the second innings against [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]].<ref name=\"9for\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1068554.html |title=Specsavers County Championship Division One, Essex v Middlesex at Chelmsford, Jun 26\u201329, 2017 |accessdate=30 June 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/40438885 |title=Essex v Middlesex: South Africa spinner Simon Harmer takes 9\u201395 as visitors collapse |accessdate=30 June 2017 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was the first bowler for Essex to take nine wickets in an innings since [[Mark Ilott]] in 1995, and he finished with career-best match figures of 14 for 172.<ref name=\"best\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2017/content/story/1107530.html |title=Magical Harmer takes Essex 29 points clear |accessdate=30 June 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\nHarmer continued his form and took the wicket which confirmed Essex as Champions in the win against Warwickshire. Harmer finished the 2017 season with the second-highest haul in the Country in terms of wickets taken, with 72 wickets at 19.19. Although neither he, nor his team, hit the same heights in 2018, he still managed 57 wickets at 24.45 each and provided useful runs batting at number eight in the batting order.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/southafrica/content/player/432960.html</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, he was named in [[Jozi Stars]]' squad for the [[2018 Mzansi Super League|first edition]] of the [[Mzansi Super League]] T20 tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/Cricket/live-mzansi-super-league-player-draft-20181017 |title=Mzansi Super League - full squad lists |work=Sport24 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/cricket/domestic/mzansi-super-league-player-draft-the-story-so-far-17521199 |title=Mzansi Super League Player Draft: The story so far |work=Independent Online |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> He was the leading wicket-taker for Warriors in the [[2018\u201319 CSA 4-Day Franchise Series]], with 27 dismissals in seven matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12624;team=3404;type=tournament |title=4-Day Franchise Series, 2018/19 - Warriors: Batting and bowling averages |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, he was named in the squad for the [[Jozi Stars]] team for the [[2019 Mzansi Super League]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricket.co.za/news/31555/MSL-20-announces-its-T20-squads |title=MSL 2.0 announces its T20 squads |work=Cricket South Africa |accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Harmer captained Essex County Cricket Club to their first ever [[T20 Blast]] victory against the [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club]] after taking 7 wickets across both the semi-final and final on Finals Day, the most by any bowler on a T20 English Domestic Finals Day. In April 2020 he was named as one of the [[Wisden Cricketers of the Year]] for his T20 and Championship performances for Essex in the 2019 season in the 2020 edition of ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]''.<ref>{{Cite book | title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]] | edition = 2020 | author = Lawrence Booth (ed.) | publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]] | chapter = Wisden Cricketers of the Year | page = 71 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cricinfo|id=432960}}\n\n{{Essex County Cricket Club squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harmer, Simon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Kolpak cricketers]]\n[[Category:South African cricketers]]\n[[Category:South Africa Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Warriors cricketers]]\n[[Category:Eastern Province cricketers]]\n[[Category:Border cricketers]]\n[[Category:Essex cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pretoria]]\n[[Category:South African people of British descent]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African cricketer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use South African English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Simon Harmer\n| image = Simon Harmer.jpg\n| caption = Harmer in 2019\n| country = South Africa\n| fullname = Simon Ross Harmer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1989|2|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Pretoria]], [[Transvaal Province]], South Africa\n| heightft = \n| heightinch = \n| heightm = \n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[off break]]\n| role = [[All-rounder]]\n| international = true\n| testdebutdate = 2 January\n| testdebutyear = 2015\n| testdebutagainst = West Indies\n| testcap = 321\n| lasttestdate = 25 November\n| lasttestyear = 2015\n| lasttestagainst = India\n| club1 = [[Eastern Province cricket team|Eastern Province]]\n| year1 = {{nowrap|2009\u20132011}}\n| club2 = [[Warriors (cricket team)|Warriors]]\n| year2 = {{nowrap|2011\u2013present}}\n| clubnumber2 = 11\n| club3 = [[Border cricket team|Border]]\n| year3 = 2016\n| club4 = [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]]\n| year4 = {{nowrap|2017\u2013present}}\n| clubnumber4 = 11\n| club5 = [[Jozi Stars]]\n| year5 = 2018\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 5\n| runs1 = 58\n| bat avg1 = 11.60\n| 100s/50s1 = 0/0\n| top score1 = 13\n| deliveries1 = 1,148\n| wickets1 = 20\n| bowl avg1 = 29.40\n| fivefor1 = 0\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 4/61\n| catches/stumpings1 = 1/\u2013\n| column2 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches2 = 145\n| runs2 = 4,292\n| bat avg2 = 24.52\n| 100s/50s2 = 2/22\n| top score2 = 102[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries2 = 34,602\n| wickets2 = 608\n| bowl avg2 = 27.80\n| fivefor2 = 34\n| tenfor2 = 6\n| best bowling2 = 9/95\n| catches/stumpings2 = 140/\u2013\n| column3 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| matches3 = 83\n| runs3 = 1,002\n| bat avg3 = 20.44\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/0\n| top score3 = 44[[Not out|*]]\n| deliveries3 = 3,858\n| wickets3 = 78\n| bowl avg3 = 42.29\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 4/42\n| catches/stumpings3 = 55/\u2013\n| column4 = [[Twenty20|T20]]\n| matches4 = 92\n| runs4 = 635\n| bat avg4 = 19.24\n| 100s/50s4 = 0/0\n| top score4 = 43\n| deliveries4 = 1,659\n| wickets4 = 68\n| bowl avg4 = 30.72\n| fivefor4 = 0\n| tenfor4 = 0\n| best bowling4 = 4/19\n| catches/stumpings4 = 44/\u2013\n| date = 29 September\n| year = 2019\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/southafrica/content/player/432960.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n'''Simon Ross Harmer''' (born 10 February 1989) is a South African professional [[cricket]]er. He plays as an [[all-rounder]], a right handed middle order batsman and an off-break bowler, for [[Warriors cricket team|Warriors]] and has played five [[Test cricket|Test]] matches for [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]].\n\nHarmer debuted for Warriors in the 2010\u20132011 first class season against the Cape Cobras claiming 5/98 in the first innings and 1/53 in the second innings to go along with his 46 and 69 runs with the bat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/southafrica/content/player/432960.html#bataves|title=Simon Harmer|website=Cricinfo|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> He became a regular fixture in Warriors side in the 2011\u20132012 side, ending the season as leading wicket taker in his full rookie season, claiming 44 wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6838;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records \u2013 Records \u2013 SuperSport Series, 2011/12 \u2013 Most wickets \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThese performances earned him a call up for the 3rd Test against West Indies in 2014/15,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-west-indies-2014-15/content/story/815081.html|title=Harmer's call-up a warning to Tahir|publisher=|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> where he made his Test match debut for South Africa [[West Indian cricket team in South Africa in 2014\u201315|against the West Indies]] on 2 January 2015 at [[Newlands Cricket Ground|Newlands]], [[Cape Town]].<ref name=\"Test\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/722333.html |title=West Indies tour of South Africa, 3rd Test: South Africa v West Indies at Cape Town, Jan 2\u20136, 2015 |accessdate=2 January 2015 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> He took his debut Test wicket by bowling [[Devon Smith]] in the last over before the lunch break on day one<ref name=\"Test\" /> and ended the innings with figures of 3/71 from 26 overs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-west-indies-2014-15/engine/match/722333.html|title=3rd Test: South Africa v West Indies at Cape Town, Jan 2\u20136, 2015 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the 2017 season, Harmer signed for [[Essex County Cricket Club]] as a [[Kolpak ruling|Kolpak]] player.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/37719936 |title=Simon Harmer: South Africa all-rounder joins Essex on Kolpak deal |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 October 2016 |accessdate=21 October 2016 }}</ref> In June, in the [[2017 County Championship]], Harmer took 9 wickets for 95 runs in the second innings against [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]].<ref name=\"9for\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1068554.html |title=Specsavers County Championship Division One, Essex v Middlesex at Chelmsford, Jun 26\u201329, 2017 |accessdate=30 June 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/40438885 |title=Essex v Middlesex: South Africa spinner Simon Harmer takes 9\u201395 as visitors collapse |accessdate=30 June 2017 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was the first bowler for Essex to take nine wickets in an innings since [[Mark Ilott]] in 1995, and he finished with career-best match figures of 14 for 172.<ref name=\"best\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2017/content/story/1107530.html |title=Magical Harmer takes Essex 29 points clear |accessdate=30 June 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\nHarmer continued his fantastic form and took the wicket which confirmed Essex as Champions in the win against Warwickshire. Harmer finished the 2017 season with the second-highest haul in the Country in terms of wickets taken, with 72 wickets at 19.19. Although neither he, nor his team, hit the same heights in 2018, he still managed 57 wickets at 24.45 each and provided useful runs batting at number eight in the batting order.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/southafrica/content/player/432960.html</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, he was named in [[Jozi Stars]]' squad for the [[2018 Mzansi Super League|first edition]] of the [[Mzansi Super League]] T20 tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/Cricket/live-mzansi-super-league-player-draft-20181017 |title=Mzansi Super League - full squad lists |work=Sport24 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/cricket/domestic/mzansi-super-league-player-draft-the-story-so-far-17521199 |title=Mzansi Super League Player Draft: The story so far |work=Independent Online |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> He was the leading wicket-taker for Warriors in the [[2018\u201319 CSA 4-Day Franchise Series]], with 27 dismissals in seven matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12624;team=3404;type=tournament |title=4-Day Franchise Series, 2018/19 - Warriors: Batting and bowling averages |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, he was named in the squad for the [[Jozi Stars]] team for the [[2019 Mzansi Super League]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricket.co.za/news/31555/MSL-20-announces-its-T20-squads |title=MSL 2.0 announces its T20 squads |work=Cricket South Africa |accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Harmer captained Essex County Cricket Club to their first ever [[T20 Blast]] victory against the [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club]] after taking 7 wickets across both the semi-final and final on Finals Day, the most by any bowler on a T20 English Domestic Finals Day. In April 2020 he was named as one of the [[Wisden Cricketers of the Year]] for his T20 and Championship performances for Essex in the 2019 season in the 2020 edition of [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]].<ref>{{Cite book | title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]] | edition = 2020 | author = Lawrence Booth (ed.) | publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]] | chapter = Wisden Cricketers of the Year | page = 71 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cricinfo|id=432960}}\n\n{{Essex County Cricket Club squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harmer, Simon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Kolpak cricketers]]\n[[Category:South African cricketers]]\n[[Category:South Africa Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Warriors cricketers]]\n[[Category:Eastern Province cricketers]]\n[[Category:Border cricketers]]\n[[Category:Essex cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pretoria]]\n[[Category:South African people of British descent]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n", "name_user": "Johnlp", "label": "safe", "comment": "Unencyclopedic word + italicise", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Harmer"}
{"title_page": "List of Portuguese football records in other countries", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=List of Portuguese football records in other countries|timestamp=20200414171016|year=2020|month=April|day=14|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=List of Portuguese football records in other countries|date=14 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{Trivia|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n[[File:Pedro Pauleta.jpg|thumb|upright|300px|From 31 October 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publico.pt/2007/11/02/jornal/pauleta-marca-golo-100-pelo-psg--e-grava-a-ouro-o-seu-nome-em-paris-235940|title=Pauleta marca golo 100 pelo PSG e grava a ouro o seu nome em Paris|publisher=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|language=PT|first=Filipe|last=Lima|date=2 November 2007|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> to 4 October 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/paris-saint-germain/story/2648473/zlatan-ibrahimovic-becomes-psg-all-time-leading-goal-scorer|title=Zlatan Ibrahimovic nets two penalties to become PSG's all-time top scorer|publisher=ESPN FC|first=Mark|last=Rodden|date=4 October 2015|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> [[Pauleta]] was [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]'s all-time top scorer.]]\n\nIn the past, only a handful of Portuguese [[association football|footballers]] were playing in other countries, though in the last two decades, this story started to change, and now numerous Portuguese players have spread around the world's top leagues, leaving the Portuguese mark in foreign football. In the present, players such as [[Lu\u00eds Figo]], [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], [[Rui Costa]], [[Deco]], [[Paulo Futre]] and [[Ricardo Carvalho]] , [[Pauleta]], [[Sim\u00e3o Sabrosa|Sim\u00e3o]], [[Tiago Mendes|Tiago]], [[Nani]], [[Pepe (footballer, born 1983)|Pepe]] and [[Raul Meireles]].{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\nBoth Lu\u00eds Figo and Cristiano Ronaldo won the [[FIFA World Player of the Year]] award. In 2008, Ronaldo won the [[FIFA World Player of the Year]], [[Ballon d'Or]], [[UEFA Club Footballer of the Year]], [[UEFA Club Football Awards#Best Forward|UEFA Club Best Forward of the Year]] and [[European Golden Shoe]], becoming the only Portuguese footballer to win the last three trophies in a foreign club. In 2011, he won again the European Golden Shoe, this time in [[La Liga]], being the first player ever to win the trophy in two different championships. Pauleta also called attention with his goalscoring ability, becoming a three-time [[Ligue 1]] top scorer ([[2001\u201302 French Division 1#Top goalscorers|2001]], [[2005\u201306 Ligue 1#Top goalscorers|2006]] and [[2006\u201307 Ligue 1#Top goalscorers|2007]]). He also scored 109 goals for [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]], emerging as the club's all-time top scorer. Cristiano Ronaldo is the only Portuguese to win five [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] titles in foreign clubs. [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] has won the most titles with a foreign club, with 15:\nLa Liga: 2011\u201312, 2016\u201317\nCopa del Rey: 2010\u201311, 2013\u201314\nSupercopa de Espa\u00f1a: 2012, 2017\nUEFA Champions League: 2013\u201314, 2015\u201316, 2016\u201317, 2017\u201318\nUEFA Super Cup: 2014, 2017\nFIFA Club World Cup: 2014, 2016, 2017\n\n==Goalscorers==\n{{Updated|22 January 2019}}\n\n===Domestic league===\n:''Top division of the respective country only.''\n*Most goals in a domestic league: \n**'''311''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[La Liga]] ([[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]), 2009\u20132018\n*Most goals in a domestic league for a single club: \n**'''311''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[La Liga]] ([[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]), 2009\u20132018\n*Most league goals in a season: \n**'''48''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[La Liga]] ([[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]), [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312]]\n*Most goals scored in a league match: \n**'''5''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[La Liga]] ([[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]), vs. [[Granada CF|Granada]] on 5 April 2015\n*Goals in consecutive league matches: \n**'''7''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[La Liga]] ([[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]), [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312]]\n*Most hat-tricks in a single league season: \n**'''8''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[La Liga]] ([[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]), [[2014\u201315 La Liga|2014\u201315]]\n*Top league scorer with more goals in a season: \n**'''48''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[La Liga]] ([[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]), [[2014\u201315 La Liga|2014\u201315]]\n*Top league scorer with fewest goals in a season: \n**'''31''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[La Liga]] ([[Real Madrid]]), [[2013\u201314 La Liga|2013\u201314]]\n\n===All competitions===\n:''Players who have spent all seasons in the top division of the respective country.''\n*Most goals in a season in all competitions: \n**'''61''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], [[2011\u201312 Real Madrid C.F. season|2011\u201312]]\n*Most hat-tricks in a single season in all competitions: \n**'''8''' \u2013 [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], [[2014\u201315 Real Madrid C.F. season|2014\u201315]]\n*Most goals for a single club in all competitions (top ten list):\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n!\n! Name\n! Years\n! League\n! Club\n! Goals\n|-\n|1||[[Cristiano Ronaldo]]||2009\u20132018||{{flagicon|Spain}} [[La Liga]]||[[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]||align=center|'''450'''\n|-style=\"background:#EEEEFF\"\n|2||[[Cris